body: "If you analyze it I believe the very heart and soul of conservatism is libertarianism. I think conservatism is really a misnomer just as liberalism is a misnomer for the liberals — if we were back in the days of the Revolution, so-called conservatives today would be the Liberals and the liberals would be the Tories. The basis of conservatism is a desire for less government interference or less centralized authority or more individual freedom and this is a pretty general description also of what libertarianism is." - Ronald Reagan

body_html:
There is something in that - but it mostly alludes to how liberal American political thought has been. We've been liberal since the beginning, or the founding. There is no real conservative tradition in this country. What Reagan is describing as conservative has been pretty uniformly seen as (classically) liberal elsewhere in the Anglosphere historically. The Conservatives of Disraeli were not a we-hate-gubmint party. Nor were continentals like Bismarck for that matter.

Even so in more pedestrian terms the distinction is clear. Libertarians have held a lot of positions on social issues that can be characterized as radically liberal or certainly not conservative or something American conservatives have subscribed to. This goes without saying. Also, if we look to a figure like Russell Kirk, who in a real sense can be said to be the father of modern conservatism even in an American context, he was critical of libertarianism; preferring a tradition bound ethos over a slash and burn capitalist one. There isn't anything particularly conservative about capitalism by the way. Quite the opposite frankly as its function has been to uproot and remake society. It is a fact of history that its original defenders were also liberals. You only get to call this stuff conservatism really if your idea of conservatism is liberalism. Many on the right, especially those of a more agrarian or aristocratic or populist bent have also been skeptical of capitalism.

More on Kirk:

https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Russell_Kirk.jpg/300px-Russell_Kirk.jpg

Kirk developed six "canons" of conservatism, which Russello (2004) described as follows:

  1. A belief in a transcendent order, which Kirk described variously as based in tradition, divine revelation, or natural law;

  2. An affection for the "variety and mystery" of human existence;

  3. A conviction that society requires orders and classes that emphasize "natural" distinctions;

  4. A belief that property and freedom are closely linked;

  5. A faith in custom, convention, and prescription, and

  6. A recognition that innovation must be tied to existing traditions and customs, which entails a respect for the political value of prudence.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Kirk

At any rate I'm one that believes our liberal values should pretty much be rejected outright. But then I'm more the old style progressive if anything than liberal old or new or American 'conservative'. Give me Teddy Roosevelt over Ronald Reagan.
